      "target": {
        "kind": "issue",
        "state": "open",
        "locked": false,
        "title": "bug(docs): nested / indented list items in a table cell are flattened (nesting + indentation lost)",
        "body": "### What happens\n\nA **nested / indented Markdown list inside a table cell** loses its nesting and indentation. Items flatten to separate plain paragraphs, and bullet markers are handled inconsistently (sometimes stripped, sometimes kept literal). This affects both write paths.\n\nThis is a follow-up to #739 (`<br>` → line breaks in table cells) and #733/#741 (`cell-update` list content): flat line breaks now work, but **nesting does not**.\n\n### Repro\n\nPath A — markdown import:\n\n```markdown\n| label | content |\n|---|---|\n| nested | - a<br>  - a1<br>  - a2<br>- b |\n```\n\n```\ngog docs write <id> --replace --markdown --file cell.md\n```\n\nPath B — cell-update with real newlines + indentation:\n\n```\ngog docs cell-update <id> --table-index 1 --row 2 --col 2 --content $'- a\\n  - a1\\n  - a2\\n- b'\n```\n\nBoth render the cell as four flat paragraphs — `a` / `a1` / `a2` / `b` — with indentation and nesting lost.\n\n### Expected\n\nNested list structure preserved inside the cell: native bullets with nesting levels, or at minimum the indentation/markers retained so the hierarchy is visible.\n\n### Environment\n\n`gog` v0.24.0-1.\n",
